    "Özel et al. 2010; Farr et al. 2011).",
    "In contrast, at redshift z ≥ 0.4, the dominant population has a primary mass of ≥20 M.",
    "This evolution of the primary mass with redshift has several possible, non-mutually exclusive interpretations.",
    "First, we can think of a metallicity trend: in the low-redshift Universe, we expect to observe mostly BBHs born from metal-rich progenitors, whereas, in the high-redshift Universe, most BBHs should originate from metal-poor (Z ≤ 10 -4) and metal-free progenitors (Hartwig et al. 2016; Kinugawa et al. 2016; Inayoshi et al. 2017; Mapelli et al. 2017; Schneider et al. 2017; Tanikawa et al. 2021b; Costa et al. 2023).",
    "The primary mass of BBHs born from metal-rich stars is expected to peak at ∼8-12 M, because of efficient wind mass loss (Belczynski et al. 2016; Stevenson et al. 2017; Giacobbo & Mapelli 2018; Klencki et al. 2018; Kruckow et al. 2018; Spera et al. 2019; Schneider et 2021; Iorio et al. 2023; Fragos et al. 2023; Agrawal et al. 2023)."
